Docker Monitoring using (Prometheus + Grafana)

Data Flow:
Docker → metrics (9323)
   ↓
Prometheus → collects metrics (9090)
   ↓
Grafana → shows graphs (3000)

  
STEP 1 — Create 2 Ubuntu Machines

Create 2 EC2 / VM instances:

Machine 1
Name: docker-server
Purpose: Docker + Prometheus
  
Machine 2
Name: grafana-machine
Purpose: Grafana
  
Security Group Rules -
  
Grafana Machine -
  
Allow:
3000 → Anywhere

Docker Server -

Allow:
9090 → Anywhere
9323 → Anywhere


STEP 2 — Update Both Machines

SSH into both machines and run:

sudo su
apt update -y

STEP 3 — Setup Grafana Machine

Login to grafana-machine.

Install Grafana -
  
wget https://dl.grafana.com/enterprise/release/grafana-enterprise-8.4.4.linux-amd64.tar.gz
tar -zxvf grafana-enterprise-8.4.4.linux-amd64.tar.gz
cd grafana-8.4.4
./bin/grafana-server

Open Grafana UI -

Browser:
http://<grafana-public-ip>:3000

Login:

username: admin
password: admin

If this opens → Grafana ready.

STEP 4 — Setup Docker Server

SSH into docker-server.

Install Docker -
  
apt update
apt install docker.io -y
service docker start

Run test containers -

docker run -dt ubuntu
docker run -dt ubuntu

This creates containers so monitoring shows data.

STEP 5 — Install Prometheus on Docker Server

Download Prometheus -
  
wget https://github.com/prometheus/prometheus/releases/download/v2.34.0/prometheus-2.34.0.linux-amd64.tar.gz
tar zxvf prometheus-2.34.0.linux-amd64.tar.gz
cd prometheus-2.34.0.linux-amd64


STEP 6 — Enable Docker Metrics 

We tell Docker to expose metrics.

Edit docker config -
  
vi /etc/docker/daemon.json

Press i and paste:

{
  "metrics-addr" : "0.0.0.0:9323",
  "experimental" : true
}

Save:
ESC → :wq

Restart docker - 
service docker restart

Verify Docker Metrics -
Open browser:

http://<docker-server-ip>:9323/metrics

You should see long text stats.

If yes → success.

STEP 7 — Configure Prometheus to Read Docker Metrics

Edit config

Inside prometheus folder -
vi prometheus.yml

Add under scrape_configs:

- job_name: "docker"
  static_configs:
    - targets: ["localhost:9323"]

Start Prometheus - 
./prometheus

Check Prometheus UI -

http://<docker-server-ip>:9090

Go:

Status → Targets
You should see docker target UP.

If UP → Prometheus working.

STEP 8 — Connect Prometheus to Grafana

Go back to grafana-machine UI.

Add Data Source
Settings → Data Sources → Add Data Source

Choose:
Prometheus

URL:
http://<docker-server-ip>:9090

Click:
Save & Test

📊 STEP 9 — Create Monitoring Dashboard
Create Panel
+ → Dashboard → Add Panel

Try queries:

engine_daemon_container_states_containers{state="running"}
engine_daemon_container_states_containers{state="stopped"}

You’ll see container counts.

STEP 10 — For Import Ready Dashboard 

+ → Import

Dashboard ID:
21040

Choose Prometheus datasource.

You’ll get full Docker monitoring dashboard instantly.

Finally you will have:

✔ Grafana running → port 3000
✔ Prometheus running → port 9090
✔ Docker metrics → port 9323
✔ Dashboard showing container stats
